\begin_layout Subsection*
SOI substrates
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to alleviate the bottlenecks of the STM lithography we have developed
 specialized substrates to serve as a platform for this technique.
 They are entirely fabricated in a cleanroom environment at CEA LETI and
 they have these key characteristics: 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
They contain multiple sets of preimplanted contacts which can be localized
 with the STM
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Possibility to reintegrate the STM fabricated devices into CMOS process
 flow
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Low defect density Si(001)-(2x1) reconstructed and H-terminated surface
 compatible with the STM lithography
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Suppressed substrate leakage thanks to the 2D nature of the SOI structure
 and, moreover, ability to tune the carrier density by means of the backgate
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The existence of the preimplanted contacts substantially reduces the STM
 patterning time as well as sample post-processing.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:STM-surface"

\end_inset

a) shows the structure of these implants and figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:STM-surface"

\end_inset

d) shows the SEM image of a device position with two n-type and two p-type
 implants.
 The finger implants (Zone II) run towards the center of the device position
 and can be as close as 600nm to one another.
 This provides sufficient space for the patterning of the active part of
 a dopant device but at the same time, it is convenient and fast to pattern
 a connection from the dopant device to the implants.
 On the outer side, the implants are connected to large, 10um sized Zone
 I implants to facilitate the post-processing.
 Fixed position and large size of these Zone I pads makes it possible to
 use optical lithography for the contact processing and and it makes it
 possible to reintegrate the sample back into the CMOS process flow 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thuaire2016"

\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The third characteristic aims at reducing in-situ sample surface preparation
 time and it is also required, because conventional Si surface preparation
 method (flashing to temperatures above 
\begin_inset Formula $1150^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$
\end_inset

) is problematic with the SOI samples and it is not compatible with the
 presence of the contact implants.
 The prefabricated substrate can be inserted in the UHV system and it can
 be immediately used for STM lithography without the need for any further
 surface preparation procedure.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to achieve sufficient surface quality we developed a specialized
 process in the reduced pressure CVD reactor 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hartmann2002"

\end_inset

.
 The surface reconstruction step is performed at a temperature of 
\begin_inset Formula $950^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$
\end_inset

 which is sufficiently low to prevent substantial dopant diffusion.
 Although H-terminated silicon surface is relatively inert, samples exposed
 to ambient conditions turned out not to be compatible with the STM lithography.
 To solve this issue, the reconstructed substrates are covered with a sacrificia
l Si cap which undergoes the same surface reconstruction procedure.
 This is achieved by hydrophobic bonding of the substrate and cap wafer
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Rauer2013"

\end_inset

, which is followed by the last step - dicing.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
These sandwitch samples are then transfered to UHV environment where the
 cap is removed by pressing a molybdenum blade against the cleavage between
 the sample and the cap.
 In practice, we briefly heat the substrates afer opening to about 
\begin_inset Formula $300^{\circ}\mathrm{C}$
\end_inset

 in order to get rid of the gas adsorbed on the sample holder and chip itself.
 This step does not influence the surface quality but is mostly a precaution
 in order to protect the STM from accumulation of contamination and it can
 be performed in less than 2 hours.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Figures 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:STM-surface"

\end_inset

b,c and e) show typical STM micrographs of the resulting sample surface.
 Fo the STM dopant device fabrication it is critical that both pristine,
 unimplanted surface (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:STM-surface"

\end_inset

e)) as well as boron (b)) and phosphorus (c)) implanted areas have suitable
 surface quality.
 In order to keep the surface quality of the implanted areas high enough
 we introduced the concept of Zone I and Zone II implants (figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:STM-surface"

\end_inset

a)).
 The Zone I implants receive much higher implantation dose at higher energy
 in order to span across the whole device layer thickness.
 This is required for the backside contact processing 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Thuaire2016"

\end_inset

.
 However, it proved difficicult to keep the surface surface quality good
 enough at such a high implantation dose.
 For this reason, the finger implants, where STM patterning takes place,
 are only shallow extensions where lower dose at a lower energy is required.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An ultimate criterium for the surface quality is the ability to desorb the
 hydrogen resist with the STM.
 Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:STM-surface"

\end_inset

f) shows an example of a desorbed pattern (a quantum dot with two tunnel
 barrier contacts) and proves that is possible to perform STM lithography
 on these substrates.
 
\end_layout

